# Finalize the audit now

Stop broadening the search. Use the evidence already gathered in this session to write the
final saved report now.

You may do at most two small targeted file reads or shell checks, only if needed to verify
an exact location or number for a finding you already have. Do not start new lines of
investigation, do not spawn sub-agents, and do not announce more future checks.

Apply the coverage check from the original prompt one last time using the evidence already
in the transcript:
- the headline claim and its code/result path;
- the most important supporting result paths;
- training/evaluation setup mismatches;
- controls, baselines, filters, seeds, aggregation, and presentation;
- the strongest negative, null, or limiting results that narrow the headline claim;
- whether a possible issue was fixed, superseded, or still affects the final report.

Now output the final report only: a brief 2-3 sentence orientation followed by one parseable
```json findings block with the same schema (`title`, `concern`, `location`, `context`,
`issue`, `mechanism`, `confidence`). If evidence is incomplete but the concern is plausible
and result-affecting, include it with lower confidence instead of doing more exploration.
Do not include a finding if you are below 50% sure it is a genuine result-affecting issue.
Use 50-60 confidence only for concerns that are real enough for a reviewer to check but
still meaningfully uncertain.

Write the findings in plain language. For each finding, `context` must be exactly two short
paragraphs separated by a blank line: first explain the relevant claim/result, then explain
the setup or evidence needed to judge the concern. Each context paragraph should usually be
45-90 words and must have at least two sentences; it should not be a one-sentence stub.
Before emitting JSON, split each context paragraph into sentences and count them. If a
paragraph has only one sentence, add a second plain sentence that explains why that claim
matters or what evidence points to the problem. `issue` states the concrete problem
directly and should usually be 45-95 words. For an unfair
comparison, explicitly say what one side gets to see or use and what the other side has to
do without; in other words, say what each side was allowed to see or use. `mechanism` is the
"Why it matters" section: it says what the reader would wrongly believe if they trusted the
original headline or number, and makes that wrong inference easy to see in 2-3 short
sentences. Use 2-3 short sentences and at least 45 words. Avoid
unexplained acronyms in `title`, `issue`, and `mechanism`; define them immediately or keep
them only in `location`.
Do not use audit-process jargon such as "affordance", "contract", "reader-facing",
"topline", or "provenance"; replace it with ordinary wording.
Titles are shown alone in the UI. Keep each title at most 18 words, preferably 14 or fewer,
and use no acronyms or project shorthand in titles.

Keep distinct concerns separate. If the transcript contains one concern about baseline
strength and another concern about extra information or access in one condition, report both
instead of folding them into a single broad benchmark caveat. The same applies to low power,
post-hoc filtering, and overbroad headlines when each affects trust in a different way.
